{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504390"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:15:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:15:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2326"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583151"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:09:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:09:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2326"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2326"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.03,0.26,0.41,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67925"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2326"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53390"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1078"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43125"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67925"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a three-month history of intermittent and worsening pain in his right knee. The pain is particularly noticeable when he has been sitting down for some time and then gets up to walk. His knee feels stiff in the morning for up to 20 minutes and the stiffness and pain are eased by walking. He has a medical history of testicular cancer diagnosed in his early twenties. He takes no regular medications, although has been taking paracetamol for pain relief over the last month.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he exhibits an antalgic gait and favours the left side. The right knee is slightly swollen when compared to the left side, with no evidence of erythema. The patellar tap test is positive and crepitus is noted during flexion of the right knee. There is no overt joint line tenderness. Flexion on this side is limited due to pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pre-patellar Bursitis","Gout","Rheumatoid arthritis","Osteoarthritis","Patellar tendonitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man presents with a three month history of knee pain and stiffness, improved by walking. Whilst the pain in a joint affected by osteoarthritis may be aggravated by movement, walking will ease the stiffness and pain. In this case examination findings reveal mild swelling of the knee, as well as an effusion, however there is no evidence of an active inflammatory process occurring. Crepitus is a significant finding and strongly suggestive of osteoarthritis. Given these facts, as well as his age and the high prevalence of the condition, \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBursitis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to inflammation of a pre-patellar bursa, the fluid filled sac superficial to the knee joint itself. Bursitis in the knee would likely present with a higher degree of swelling, along with erythema. Crepitus is less likely to be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E is not an uncommon condition and the knee is one of the most frequently involved joints. In this case however, the pain has developed and worsened over a three-month period, an extended time course not generally seen with gout. Gout also tends to present with excruciating pain, along with marked tenderness, swelling and erythema. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E and the associated joint pain can often be improved by physical activity, like in this case. Despite this, rheumatoid arthritis generally involves multiple small joints, particularly of the hands and feet. A monoarticular arthritis of the knee would be an unusual presentation, making rheumatoid arthritis an incorrect answer option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatellar tendonitis \u003C/strong\u003Erefers to inflammation of the patellar tendon. Also called \u0022jumper\u0027s knee\u0022, it is commonly seen in athletes, particularly those who play sports such as volleyball and basketball. In patellar tendonitis, the pain typically gets worse with repetitive movement and activity, rather than relieved as seen in this patient. In addition, most patients will have localised tenderness over the patella tendon. This man has no focal tenderness, making patellar tendonitis a less likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pain and stiffness in osteoarthritis can be lessened by walking."],"references":["Bunt CW, Jonas CE, Chang JG. Knee Pain in Adults and Adolescents: The Initial Evaluation. Am Fam Physician. 2018;98:576-85. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30325638/","Sharma L. Osteoarthritis of the Knee. N Engl J Med. 2021;384:51-59. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMcp1903768"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53390"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2326"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53390"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T20:58:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T20:58:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2326"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67925"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":